          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Travel across the Gulf is about to get much easier. The latest Unified Tourist Visa, also known as the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.dubaisummary.com/ds-25-jul-25-spotlight-h2-4-gcc-grand-tours-visa?source=website" target="_blank">GCC Grand Tours Visa</a>, will shortly allow visitors to enter Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, and the UAE with a single permit instead of applying separately for each country.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            The system (approved in 2023 and expected to launch by late 2025 or early 2026) will be fully online, with one application portal for all six countries. It’s designed for tourism, short stays, and visiting family or friends, rather than work or long-term residence.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           Exact fees and validity (most probably 30–90 days) are yet to be announced, but it’s expected to be more budget-friendly than six separate visas. This latest system aims to make multi‑country Gulf trips as seamless as a Schengen‑style journey in Europe (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.dubaisummary.com/ds-25-jul-25-spotlight-h2-5-about-schengen-visa?source=website" target="_blank">about Schengen visa</a>).
