            When Dubai opened its first airport
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           Back in the 1950s, Dubai didn’t have its airport. Travelers landed in Sharjah instead, as the British Royal Air Force (RAF) had a base there and preferred to maintain control over regional activities. Passengers heading to Dubai had to drive the rest of the way.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            But Sheikh Rashid bin Saeed (first vice president and second prime minister of the UAE) had bigger plans. He saw how air travel could open Dubai to trade and visitors, and despite British resistance, he pushed ahead. With help from former RAF pilot Freddie Bosworth, construction began on a site in Al Ghusais. In 1959, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #102341; color: black;" href="https://link.dubaisummary.com/ds-25-jul-25-amih-h1-18-dubai-s-very-first-airport?source=website" target="_blank">Dubai’s very first airport</a> opened, with a compacted sand runway.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            In the early days, Middle East Airlines and Kuwait Airways flew small propeller planes into Dubai. The runway wasn’t always up to the challenge. More powerful aircraft often blew sand away, forcing repairs. The terminal was just a simple building with two duty-free shops and a single immigration desk. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            It’s almost impossible to imagine those humble sand strips when you step into Dubai International Airport. What began as a single runway and a wooden desk has evolved into one of the world's busiest airports, connecting over 240 destinations and handling innumerable passengers annually.
          </p>
